title: User query: Plan description from client LLM
log: Generate a Wayang plan that computes the total discounted revenue for shipments between the nations ‘GERMANY’ and ‘FRANCE’ during 1995 and 1996. Revenue is l_extendedprice * (1 - l_discount). Join supplier, lineitem, orders, customer, and the nation tables, and keep only rows where the supplier is from one of the two nations and the customer is from the other. Use only shipments with l_shipdate between 1995-01-01 and 1996-12-31, extract the shipment year, and group results by supplier nation, customer nation, and year. Output in a textfile.

title: Agent: SpecifierAgent Output
log: Generate a Wayang plan that computes the total discounted revenue for shipments between the nations Germany and France during 1995 and 1996. The revenue is calculated as l_extendedprice * (1 - l_discount). The plan must join the following tables: supplier, lineitem, orders, customer, and nation. Include only rows where the supplier’s nation is either Germany or France and the customer’s nation is the other one (i.e., one nation per row, supplier and customer in opposite nations). Use only shipments with l_shipdate between 1995-01-01 and 1996-12-31. Extract the shipment year from l_shipdate and group the results by supplier nation, customer nation, and year. Output the final results to a text file.

log.thoughts: Selected tables that are directly used in the query: supplier, lineitem, orders, customer, and nation. No text files are needed for this plan.

steps.detailed_description: Load the following input sources: supplier, lineitem, orders, customer, nation. Each input provides all columns as defined in the data information and will be used to build the combined shipment view.

Join lineitem with orders on l_orderkey to associate line items with orders. Then join the result with supplier on l_suppkey = s_suppkey to tie shipments to suppliers. Next, join supplier with nation on s_nationkey = n_nationkey to get supplier nation name, and join orders with customer on o_custkey = c_custkey, then join customer with nation on c_nationkey = n_nationkey to obtain customer nation name. The resulting dataset should include: supplier nation name, customer nation name, l_extendedprice, l_discount, l_shipdate, and any required keys for grouping and filtering.

Filter rows where l_shipdate is between 1995-01-01 and 1996-12-31 inclusive. Further filter to include only shipments where the supplier nation is Germany or France and the customer nation is the other nation (i.e., supplier nation and customer nation are the two nations in {GERMANY, FRANCE} and differ). Compute the per-row revenue as l_extendedprice * (1 - l_discount). Extract the shipment year from l_shipdate. Then group by supplier nation name, customer nation name, and year, aggregating the sum of revenue to produce total discounted revenue per (supplier nation, customer nation, year).

Write the aggregated results to a text file in a tabular format suitable for downstream consumption. Ensure the output includes columns: supplier_nation, customer_nation, year, total_discounted_revenue.

log.thoughts: We construct a compact, acyclic plan with four steps: load all sources, perform a comprehensive join to enrich shipments with nation contexts, filter and compute revenue by year and nation pairing, then output to a text file. This satisfies the nation-pair constraint and the required date and revenue formula.
